  "text": "Recently, we reported that adherent platelets cause CD34 ϩ cell differentiation to endothelial cells. [CITATION_1] To further evaluate the molecular requirements of platelet-dependent differentiation of progenitor cells, CD34 ϩ cells were coincubated with isolated platelets as described previously. Isolated CD34 ϩ cells were allowed to adhere to immobilized platelets, immobilized fibronectin, or collagen and were cultivated in endothelial cell growth medium as described previously. [CITATION_2] CD34 ϩ cells formed colonies on immobilized platelets similar to immobilized fibronectin, which indicates differentiation into endothelial cells ( Figure 7A and 7B ). After 5 days, the morphology of initially round CD34 ϩ cells on immobilized platelets evolved into adherent spindle-shaped cells that were positive for von Willebrand factor and revealed typical cytoskeletal rearrangement as demonstrated by phalloidin staining ( Figure 7C ). In contrast, virtually no colonies were formed on collagen, which is the major extracellular matrix protein ( Figure 7A and 7B ). The number of colonies formed on immobilized platelets was significantly higher than in fibronectin or collagen wells (mean number of coloniesϮSEM: platelets versus fibronectin versus collagen 12Ϯ0.84 versus 8.9Ϯ0.7 versus 1Ϯ1, PϽ0.001; Figure 7A and 7B).",
